<h1 class="rm-manual">Coronavirus Diary (3): Creeping Death</h1>
<p class="rm-manual"> Posted on <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/2020/03/17/coronavirus-journal-3-creeping-death/" rel="bookmark">March 17, 2020</a><span> by <span><a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/author/khawajaenator/" rel="author">Irfan Khawaja</a></span></span><span> under <a href="https://irfankhawajaphilosopher.com/category/covid-19/" rel="category tag">COVID-19</a></span> </p>
<p class="rm-manual">Tomorrow, and tomorrow, and tomorrow,</p>
<p class="rm-manual">Creeps in this petty pace from day to day,</p>
<p class="rm-manual">To the last syllable of recorded time;</p>
<p class="rm-manual">And all our yesterdays have lighted fools</p>
<p class="rm-manual">The way to dusty death. Out, out, brief candle!</p>
<p class="rm-manual">Lifeâ€™s but a walking shadow, a poor player,</p>
<p class="rm-manual">That struts and frets his hour upon the stage,</p>
<p class="rm-manual">And then is heard no more. It is a tale</p>
<p class="rm-manual">Told by an idiot, full of sound and fury,</p>
<p class="rm-manual">Signifying nothing.</p>
<p class="rm-manual">â€“Shakespeare, Macbeth, Act V, Scene 5</p>
<p>I count it as a great blessing that I have so far, at age fifty, 
managed to avoid becoming a father. Amusingly enough, my ex-wife once 
told me, flat out, â€œBefore I met you, I was on the fence about having 
children. I no longer am. You would make a terrible father. So Iâ€™ve 
abandoned the idea.â€ Music to my ears.</p>
<p>And yet, Iâ€™ve just had a phone conversation with one of my best 
friends, in which he asked me whether I would temporarily take custody 
of his child in the event that both he and his wife die of COVID-19. 
â€œYes,â€ I say, without hesitation. I actually like his kid, as kids go. 
Granted, the custody he imagines is temporary, until family members 
could come and do a formal adoption. My friend knows me well enough to 
know that coronavirus or no, it makes little sense to turn me into a 
bona fide step-father. One catastrophe is enough.</p>
<p>As he thinks this deeply unpalatable matter through, heâ€™s 
simultaneously forced to work through a set of tedious and mostly 
unanswerable legal questions. Would the State permit a teenaged child to
 live without a guardian in the event of his parentsâ€™ decease? Or would 
the child be sucked into the Stateâ€™s <a href="https://www.nj.gov/dcf/contact/dcpplocal/" rel="noopener">â€œchild protectionâ€ bureaucracy</a>?
 Would the State permit a non-blood-relative like me to assume a 
temporary custodial role, or would it overrule the arrangement? Would it
 help to write out an advance directive, and notarize it? How much 
longer are notaries going to be in operation, anyway? Lots of questions 
here, but a hell of a time to have to hire a lawyer.</p>
<p>I tell him that I find it inconceivable that the State would insist 
on such legal niceties under circumstances like these. â€œThat would defy 
common sense,â€ I say with great confidence. My friend laughs. â€œCommon 
sense. I like that. Suddenly, the State operates on the basis of common 
sense.â€ I open my mouth to respond, but oddly, no articulate sound 
emerges. The sentence I have in mind begins, â€œBut surelyâ€¦â€ and fizzles 
out after that.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.amazon.com/Our-Enemy-State-Albert-Nock/dp/1502585634" rel="noopener">Our Friend, the State</a>:
 the minor deity to whose prudence and foresight we owe our welfare. But
 hell, Iâ€™m not an anarchist. Iâ€™m realist enough to know that we need the
 State. Where would we be without it? If we didnâ€™t have a State, after 
all, who would tie us up in bureaucratic knots when we had heart-rending
 decisions to make about the fate of our loved ones, in the wake of the 
disasters the agencies of the State failed to predict and stop?*</p>
<p>I could quit there with a nice, snarky, libertarianish polemic 
against the State. But the truth is, the call didnâ€™t end there. It ended
 with our favorite topic of conversation, a workplace story. My 
libertarian friends have been serving up heart-warming stories on 
Facebook about the beneficent power of markets in coping with the 
coronavirus. I wish I could share their enthusiasm, but after my 
friendâ€™s story, I donâ€™t. Not that I really did before it.</p>
<p>There was a lot of background noise on the call. â€œWhere the hell are you?â€ I ask him. â€œWhatâ€™s all that noise?â€</p>
<p>â€œIâ€™m in the car,â€ he says wearily, â€œcoming back from work. Itâ€™s noisy.â€</p>
<p>â€œFrom work?â€ I ask incredulously. â€œWhat the fuck are you doing at 
work? I thought you worked in some hi-tech office. Youâ€™re telling me 
theyâ€™re not set up for online operations? I work for a fucking 
university, and we transitioned to online operations last week.â€</p>
<p>â€œThey are set up for online operations,â€ he responds. â€œI mean, we are.â€</p>
<p>â€œNot 100%, you mean?â€</p>
<p>â€œNo, 100%, including my job. Everyone. Weâ€™re 100% set up for online 
business. They told us flat-out that they had a â€˜business continuity 
planâ€™ that would allow every one of us to work from home anytime they 
decided to put it into effect.â€</p>
<p>I canâ€™t help laughing. â€œWhat the fuck? So what are they waiting for? A divine mandate?â€</p>
<p>â€œWell, yeah, sort of,â€ he says. â€œThey havenâ€™t been ordered by the 
State to close, not yet. So they havenâ€™t. I mean, no liability if they 
donâ€™t, right? Theyâ€™re going to maintain a â€˜physical presence at the 
siteâ€™ until they get a legal order to close down.â€</p>
<p>Long pause.</p>
<p>â€œWhy?â€ I ask. The old Nazi line â€œ<a href="https://aaeblog.com/2010/02/17/hier-ist-kein-warum/" rel="noopener">hier ist kein warum</a>â€œ
 goes briefly through my head. Absurd, irrelevant free association, I 
think, and suppress it, only to hear the dim echoes of another 
Germanic-sounding free association drift in. Itâ€™s garbledâ€“â€œfluidity, 
security, reckless something somethingâ€â€“so after the call, I pick the 
relevant book off the shelf and turn to what it actually says:</p>
<p>Thus large scale industry, by its very essence, necessitates 
variations of labour, fluidity of functions, and mobility of the worker 
in all directions. But on the other hand, in its capitalist form it 
reproduces the old division of labor with its ossified particularities. 
We have seen how this absolute contradiction does away with all repose, 
all fixity and all security as far as the workerâ€™s life-situation is 
concerned; how it constantly threatens, by taking away the instruments 
of labor, to snatch from his hands the means of subsistence, and by 
