<p>LOL. Now Iâ€™m channeling Marx! The mind does strange things under duress.</p>
<p>â€œWell, they just said that they wanted business continuity,â€ he says,
 matter-of-factly. â€œUsed that phrase a lot. â€˜Business continuity, 
physical presence,â€™ shit like that. In other words, they want to convey 
the impression to the outside world that business continues. It looks 
bad if no one is there. Doesnâ€™t matter that they donâ€™t need to be there.
 In the corporate sense, we do need to be there.â€</p>
<p>Long pause. â€œIt looks bad.â€ They canâ€™t be serious. But capitalism is 
serious business. Iâ€™ve got one hand holding the phone, so Iâ€™ve only got 
the other one free to cover my face. I feel a strong urge to drop the 
phone and cover it with both.</p>
<p>â€œThatâ€™s fucking outrageous,â€ I say, at last. â€œBut when this shit is 
over, thereâ€™ll be a reckoning for these people.â€ Iâ€™m yelling now. 
â€œThereâ€™ll be hell to pay.â€</p>
<p>â€œNo, there wonâ€™t,â€ he says.</p>
<p>Long pause.</p>
<p>The call ends soon after that. Heâ€™s got to go. Itâ€™s late, and heâ€™s got work tomorrow.</p>
<p>*As I wrote this post, I could hear my wife Alison, a 
psychotherapist, talking a colleague through the regulatory hurdles 
